<section label="separable-form">
	<title>Separable Form</title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Some differential equations can be rewritten so that all the <m>x</m> terms are on one side and all the <m>y</m> terms are on the other. Such equations are called <em>separable</em>, which is defined more precisely as follows.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<subsection>
		<title>Definition of Separable &amp; Separable Form</title>

		<definition xml:id="separable">
			<title>Separable Form</title>

			<statement>
				<p>
					A first-order differential equation is <term>separable</term> if it can be written in the following <term>separable form</term>
					<men xml:id="separable-form">
						\dfrac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y)
					</men>.
				</p>
			</statement>

		</definition>

		<p>
			The notation, <m>f(x) \cdot g(y)</m>, can seem strange at first glance, so let's break it down.
		</p>

		<p>
			Here, <m>f(x)</m> is just a stand-in for any expression that only involves the variable <m>x</m> and possibly a constant. For example, it might be:
			<me>
				13\sin(3x), \quad 3x - 2e^{4x}, \quad \dfrac{2^x}{1+x}, \quad 1, \quad \text{etc.}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Likewise, <m>g(y)</m> stands for any expression involving only <m>y</m> and constants:
			<me>
				\sin(y+\cos y), \quad 3y^2 + 1, \quad \dfrac{1}{y}, \quad 1, \quad \text{etc.}
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			So when we say <m>f(x) \cdot g(y)</m>, we just mean any product where one factor depends only on <m>x</m> and the other only on <m>y</m>.
		</p>

		<exercise label="sov-form-cyu-1">

			<statement>
				<p>
					Match each expression to the function notation that best describes it.
					<me/><!-- Vertical space hack. Is there a better way? -->
				</p>

				<sidebyside widths="36% 64%">
					<p><m>\color{RoyalBlue}\small\text{Expression}\ ⤵︎ </m></p>
					<p><m>\color{BurntOrange}\small\text{Function Notation}\ ⤵︎</m></p>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>

			<cardsort>

				<match>
					<premise> <m>\sqrt{x} + 1	</m></premise>
					<response><m>f(x)					</m></response>
				</match>

				<match>
					<premise> <m>\ln(y)		</m></premise>
					<premise> <m>y^2 + y	</m></premise>
					<response><m>g(y)			</m></response>
				</match>

				<match>
					<premise> <m>3y + x\cos(x)	</m></premise>
					<response><m>f(x) + g(y)		</m> </response>
				</match>

				<match>
					<premise> <m>ye^x							</m></premise>
					<premise> <m>(x^2+3)(y-1)			</m></premise>
					<response><m>f(x) \cdot g(y)	</m> </response>
				</match>

				<match>
					<premise> <m>\sqrt{x+y}			</m></premise>
					<response> None of the Above </response>
				</match>
			</cardsort>

		</exercise>

	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Separable Differential Equations</title>

		<p>
			Now that the notation makes sense, here are some examples of differential equations in separable form:
			<me>
				\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \ub{(x^2 + 1) \cdot (y - 6)}_{\large f(x)\ \cdot\ g(y)}, \qquad
				\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \ub{\sin(y) \cdot \cos(x)}_{\large g(y)\ \cdot\ f(x)}.
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Differential equations can still be separable even if one of the variables does not explicitly appear. For example, all of these equations are separable:
			<ul marker="square">
				<li><m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 6x + 5 = (6x + 5) \cdot (1)\qquad \leftarrow\ f(x) \cdot g(y)</m></li>
				<li><m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = P\ (P-1) = (1) \cdot (\ P\ (P-1)\ )\qquad \leftarrow\ f(t) \cdot g(P)</m></li>
				<li><m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 15 = (3) \cdot (5)\qquad \leftarrow\ f(x) \cdot g(y)</m></li>
			</ul>
		</p>

	</subsection>

	<subsection>
		<title>Non-Separable Differential Equations</title>

		<p>
			As important as it is to show an equation is separable, it is equally important to identify when it is not. The next example demonstrates some non-separable equations.
		</p>

		<example xml:id="example-non-separable">

			<statement>
				<p>
					Explain why the differential equations are NOT separable.
					<ol marker="A." cols="3">
						<li><m>\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} = xy^2</m></li>
						<li><m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = -6x + 2y</m></li>
						<li><m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \cos(xy)</m></li>
					</ol>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>

				<p>
					<ol marker="A.">
						<li>
							<p>
								The first equation is a bit of a trick question to remind you of the first-order requirement of a separable equation. Since this equation is second-order, <em>separability does not apply</em>.
							</p>
						</li>
						<li>
							<p>
								The second equation is first-order, but it is not separable since <m>-6x + 2y</m> cannot be expressed in the function-notation form <m>f(x) \cdot g(y)</m>.
							</p>
						</li>
						<li>
							<p>
								The last equation is first-order, but there are no trigonometric identities that you could apply to <m>\cos(xy)</m> to separate the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> parts by multiplication.
							</p>
						</li>
					</ol>
				</p>


			</solution>

		</example>

		<exercise label="sov-form-cyu-2">

			<task label="sov-form-cyu-2-task-1">
				<statement>
					<p>
						Which of the following differential equations is not separable?
					</p>
				</statement>

				<choices randomize="yes">
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \sin(x)\cos(y)</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. This equation is separable because it can be expressed as a product of functions involving only <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\dfrac{dy}{dx} = e^x \cdot y^2</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. This equation is separable as the variables are already separated by multiplication.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\dfrac{dy}{dx} = x + y</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! This equation is not separable because the terms involving <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are added together, not multiplied.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \dfrac{x}{y}</m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. This equation is separable because <m>\frac{x}{y}</m> can be expressed as <m>\frac{x}{1} \cdot \frac{1}{y}</m>.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="sov-form-cyu-2-task-2">

				<statement>
					<p>
						Select each of the separable differential equations below.
					</p>
				</statement>

				<areas>
					<tabular>
						<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
						<row>
							<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\normalsize\dfrac{dy}{dx} = xy^2						</m></area></cell><cell/>
							<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\normalsize\dfrac{dz}{dt} = \cos^2 z				</m></area></cell><cell/>
							<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\normalsize\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \ln(x)\tan(y)	</m></area></cell>
						</row>
						<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
						<row>
							<cell><area correct="no"><m>\normalsize\dfrac{dy}{dx} = y - x^2	</m></area></cell><cell/>
							<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\normalsize\dfrac{dy}{dx} = \pi		</m></area></cell><cell/>
							<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\normalsize\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 1 - y	</m></area></cell>
						</row>
						<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
						<row>
							<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\normalsize\dfrac{dy}{dx} = y^2		</m></area></cell><cell/>
							<cell><area correct="no"><m>\normalsize\dfrac{dy}{dx} = x - 3y	</m></area></cell><cell/>
							<cell><area correct="yes"><m>\normalsize\dfrac{dy}{dx} = -44		</m></area></cell>
						</row>
						<row><cell><m/></cell></row>
					</tabular>
				</areas>

				<feedback>
					<p>
						Remember, a differential equation is separable if you can express it as a product of functions of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> separately. Look for equations in which the variables are separated by multiplication, not by addition or other operations.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</task>

